<!-- SECTION 3 — ORDER FINDING = PERIOD FINDING -->
<!-- ══════════════════════════════════════ -->
<section class="section" id="s3">
<div class="section-num">Section 03</div>
<h2>Order Finding = Period Finding</h2>

<p>The order problem has a beautiful signal-processing interpretation. Let's define the function:</p>

<div class="def">
  <div class="def-title">The Modular Exponentiation Function</div>
  <div class="math-block">
    <div class="eq">f(ℓ) = x<sup>ℓ</sup> mod n &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; ℓ = 0, 1, 2, ...</div>
  </div>
  This function is <strong>periodic with period r</strong>:
  <div class="math-block" style="margin-top:0.4rem;">
    <div class="eq">f(ℓ) = x<sup>ℓ</sup> mod n = x<sup>(ℓ+r)</sup> mod n = f(ℓ+r) &nbsp;&nbsp; for all ℓ</div>
    <div class="eq-note">&nbsp;&nbsp;Because x<sup>r</sup> mod n = 1, so multiplying by x<sup>r</sup> changes nothing.</div>
  </div>
</div>

<div class="insight">
  <strong>The chain of reductions:</strong>
  <div class="math-block" style="margin-top:0.5rem;">
    <div class="mstep"><div class="mstep-label" style="font-size:1rem;">Factoring n</div><div class="mstep-body c-b">≡ &nbsp;Order finding of x mod n (for random x)</div></div>
    <div class="mstep"><div class="mstep-label" style="font-size:1rem;">Order finding</div><div class="mstep-body c-g">≡ &nbsp;Period finding of f(ℓ) = x<sup>ℓ</sup> mod n</div></div>
    <div class="mstep"><div class="mstep-label" style="font-size:1rem;">Period finding</div><div class="mstep-body c-o">≡ &nbsp;Finding peaks in the Fourier transform of f</div></div>
  </div>
</div>

